'''Nagigama''' (薙鎌) is a {{ill|weapon|ja|武器|12=draft}} consisting of a cylindrical wooden shaft approximately seven {{ill|shaku|ja|尺|12=draft}} (about 210 {{ill|centimeters|ja|センチメートル|en|12=draft}}) long, with a short {{ill|Chokutō|ja|直刀|Chokutō=Chokutō|lt=straight blade|12=draft}} mounted perpendicularly at the tip, with the blade facing inward. It is used for slashing, thrusting, cutting, hooking an opponent to throw them off balance, or decapitating. Depending on the martial arts school, it is also known as '''Nagarakama''' (長柄鎌) or '''Yaegama''' (八重鎌). It is believed to have originated from long-handled sickles used for cutting aquatic plants tangled around boats.

The nagigama was part of the {{ill|samurai|ja|武士|12=draft}}'s armament, alongside weapons like the {{ill|naginata|ja|薙刀|12=draft}} and {{ill|spear|ja|槍|12=draft}}, and was reportedly used as early as the {{ill|Genpei War|ja|治承・寿永の乱|12=draft}}. However, it has largely disappeared since the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|文明開化|12=draft}}, with only a few martial arts schools continuing to teach its techniques.

Current martial arts schools that use the nagigama include the {{ill|Fusen-ryū|ja|不遷流柔術|en|Fusen-ryū=Fusen-ryū|lt=Takeda-ryu Yaegama|12=draft}}. Additionally, some {{ill|kusarigamajutsu|ja|鎖鎌術|en|12=draft}} styles incorporate a nagigama with a weighted chain attached, creating a form of {{ill|kusarigama|ja|鎖鎌|12=draft}}.

At {{ill|Suwa Shrine|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|12=draft}}, the nagigama is considered one of the sacred treasures ({{ill|shinki|ja|神器|12=draft}}). The blade is shaped like a rooster’s comb and symbolizes the pioneering of the Shinano region by the Suwa deity. The name "nagi" is also associated with "calm" (凪ぐ), representing protection against storms and disasters, and the idea of "warding off various misfortunes."

